\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.3}{\ignorespaces Example of spread-target quantisation on a Try~79 test sample (Jaipur, \texttt  {sample\_07308}). The ground-truth delay-spread map contains broad staircase-like bands and isolated quantised pixels, while the height-aware calibrated prediction is smoother and more continuous. The resulting delay RMSE is only \SI {1.11}{ns}, but the residual panel shows how RMSE still penalises smooth transitions across quantised ground-truth boundaries. The same effect is visible on the angular-spread map, whose target is dominated by sparse high-valued quantised pixels.}}{112}{figure.caption.140}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:try79_quantized_spread_example}{{4.3}{112}{Example of spread-target quantisation on a Try~79 test sample (Jaipur, \texttt {sample\_07308}). The ground-truth delay-spread map contains broad staircase-like bands and isolated quantised pixels, while the height-aware calibrated prediction is smoother and more continuous. The resulting delay RMSE is only \SI {1.11}{ns}, but the residual panel shows how RMSE still penalises smooth transitions across quantised ground-truth boundaries. The same effect is visible on the angular-spread map, whose target is dominated by sparse high-valued quantised pixels}{figure.caption.140}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.4}{\ignorespaces Try 77 DirectML test RMSE per expert, separated by spread target. For each topology class, paired bars show sample-mean and pixel-weighted aggregation. Dashed grey lines mark the original project targets (\SI {50}{ns} for delay spread, \(20^\circ \) for angular spread). The angular-spread experts beat the target across all topology classes; the delay-spread experts also remain below \SI {50}{ns}, but their pixel-weighted errors are larger and less competitive with the later Try 79 ridge calibration.}}{113}{figure.caption.141}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:try77_per_expert}{{4.4}{113}{Try 77 DirectML test RMSE per expert, separated by spread target. For each topology class, paired bars show sample-mean and pixel-weighted aggregation. Dashed grey lines mark the original project targets (\SI {50}{ns} for delay spread, \(20^\circ \) for angular spread). The angular-spread experts beat the target across all topology classes; the delay-spread experts also remain below \SI {50}{ns}, but their pixel-weighted errors are larger and less competitive with the later Try 79 ridge calibration}{figure.caption.141}{}}
